# Creating a Pull Request

When asked to create a PR, you will be given a **source branch** and a **destination (base) branch**.

## Steps

1. **Gather context**: Run `git log <base>...<source> --oneline` and `git diff <base>...HEAD` to understand all commits and changes included in the PR.
2. **Read the PR template** at `.cursor/assets/pr-template.md`.
3. **Fill out the template** by analyzing the diff and commit history:
   - **Description**: Write a concise summary of what the PR accomplishes.
   - **Details**: Explain the implementation approach, link relevant issues, and note any new dependencies.
   - **Testing / Security / SOC 2 checklists**: Leave the checkboxes unchecked — the author will confirm these manually.
4. **Create the PR** using the GitHub CLI:

```bash
git push -u origin <source>

gh pr create \
  --base <destination> \
  --head <source> \
  --title "<concise PR title>" \
  --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
<filled-in template content>
EOF
)"
```

5. **Return the PR URL** to the user after creation.

## Formatting Rules

- The PR title should ALWAYS start with the Linear issue identifier (e.g. ENG-2023) 
- The PR title should be a short, imperative sentence (e.g., "Add roadmap filtering by status").
- Directly below the Description, include an "Illustrations" section, which includes a visual demo (image/video) of a before and after of each fix. If it is adding an entirely new feature, subtitle the feature image/video accordingly. Prefer using a video of length 10 - 20 seconds to showcase the entire feature.
- Keep the Description section to 1-3 sentences.
- In Details, use bullet points for multiple items.
- Preserve all checklist sections from the template exactly as they appear.
- Use GitHub-flavored markdown throughout.
- REMOVE the final "Made with Cursor" text at the bottom of the PR description. This should be removed.